# Vercel Web Analytics Installation

Successfully installed and configured Vercel Web Analytics for this Next.js App Router project.

## Changes Made

### 1. Installed @vercel/analytics Package
- Added `@vercel/analytics` (version 1.6.1) to project dependencies
- Used npm to install the package as indicated by the existing package-lock.json

### 2. Updated Root Layout (src/app/layout.tsx)
- Imported `Analytics` component from '@vercel/analytics/next'
- Added `<Analytics />` component inside the `<body>` tag, after `{children}`
- This enables automatic page view tracking and web vitals collection

### 3. Updated Dependency Files
- package.json: Added @vercel/analytics to dependencies
- package-lock.json: Updated with new dependency and its sub-dependencies

## Implementation Details

The project uses Next.js App Router architecture with the root layout at `src/app/layout.tsx`. Following Vercel's best practices:
- The Analytics component is placed at the root layout level for global tracking
- It's positioned inside the body tag after the children, which is the recommended placement
- No additional configuration is needed - analytics will work automatically when deployed to Vercel

## Testing Performed

1. ✅ Build test: `npm run build` completed successfully
2. ✅ Linting: Ran `npm run lint` - no new errors introduced by our changes
3. ✅ The Analytics component integrates cleanly with existing code structure

## Notes

- The Analytics component will automatically track page views and Web Vitals when the app is deployed to Vercel
- In local development, analytics are disabled by default
- No environment variables or additional configuration are required
- The implementation follows Next.js 13+ App Router patterns with proper TypeScript typing
